    <text id="F0393T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p> Christian Geisel writes to his younger brother Franklin to inquire about his
                    life and ask him about a new horse. </p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Franklin Geisel </name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1863-06-06">June 6<hi rend="super">th</hi> 1863 </date>
                        <name type="place">Camp near Catletts Station </name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Brother Franklin </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I was very <del rend="none" hand="h1"/> of may 30<hi rend="super">th</hi> and to hear that
                    you were all well. As I received your letter with Sister Louisa's. I thought I
                    would also send you a few lines again with her letter, which i hope may find you
                    all in as good health as I enjoy at present. I expect you have grown a good deal
                    since I saw you last, as I see by your letter you bear on the plough now which
                    William used to do for me. Have you got the old horses yet, Thom, Perry and
                    Bill? I have a little gray secesh pony now, I wish I could give you a ride on
                    him, he is quiet as a little dog, I call him Taylor<pb n="2"/>Give my love to
                    Willimina and Frad and William and the rest. I can write no more this time and
                    will be happy soon to hear from you again. From </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Your affectionate Brother </salute>
                    <signed>Christian Geisel </signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">Co. H 6<hi rend="super">th</hi> Penn. Cavalry, Army of
                        the Potomac <name type="recipient">Franklin P. Geisel <del rend="none" hand="h1"/> Bucks
                            County Penn. </name>
                    </seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
